T1  - The causal direction between money and prices: An alternative approach
AU  - Hoover, Kevin D.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 27
IS  - 3
SP  - 381
EP  - 423
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/06/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(91)90015-G
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030439329190015G
AB  - Causality is viewed as a matter of control. Controllability is captured in Simon's analysis of causality as an asymmetrical relation of recursion between variables in the unobservable data-generating process. Tests of the stability of marginal and conditional distributions for these variables can provide evidence of causal ordering. The causal direction between prices and money in the United States 1950–1985 is assessed. The balance of evidence supports the view that money does not cause prices, and that prices do cause money.
ER  - 

